Atmospheric greenhouse gas concentrations (CSI 013) - Assessment published Oct 2005 climate csi The atmospheric concentration of carbon dioxide (CO2), the main greenhouse gas, has increased by 34 % compared with pre-industrial levels as a result of human activities, with an accelerated rise since 1950. Other greenhouse gas concentrations have also risen as a result of human activities. The present concentrations of CO2 and CH4 have not been exceeded during the past 420 000 years and the present N2O concentration during at least the past 1 000 years.

IPCC (2001) baseline projections show that greenhouse gas concentrations are likely to exceed the level of 550 ppm CO2-equivalent in the next few decades (before 2050).
